1
00:02:14,884 --> 00:02:19,013
This is a. 44 Magnum,
the most powerful handgun in the world.

2
00:02:19,848 --> 00:02:22,016
And it could blow your head clean off.

3
00:02:23,268 --> 00:02:24,477
Do you feel lucky?

4
00:02:30,316 --> 00:02:33,820
Mr. Ricca!
How do you feel about your acquittal?

5
00:02:33,987 --> 00:02:37,365
It proves what I always said,
I had nothing to do with Scarza's murder.

6
00:02:37,532 --> 00:02:39,909
Who could have killed
Anthony Scarza and his family?

7
00:02:40,076 --> 00:02:42,662
That's a stupid question. Get off my back!

8
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:47,167
Mr. Weinstein, explain the technicality
involving the lack of admissible evidence.

9
00:02:47,333 --> 00:02:50,295
That's a legality
that can't be explained at this time.

10
00:02:50,461 --> 00:02:53,214
Mr. Weinstein, you don't seem surprised
about the decision.

11
00:02:53,381 --> 00:02:55,884
I don't know why they waste
the taxpayers' money.

12
00:02:56,050 --> 00:03:00,013
This whole thing is an arbitrary attack
on a legitimate businessman.

13
00:03:00,471 --> 00:03:02,265
- Do you have any comments?
- What, dear?

14
00:03:02,432 --> 00:03:04,100
Do you have any other comments?

15
00:03:04,267 --> 00:03:06,603
I'll give you a comment:
Their minds are dead.

16
00:03:06,769 --> 00:03:09,105
- What do you mean by that?
- Their minds are dead.

17
00:03:09,272 --> 00:03:11,774
Mr. Ricca means he is very pleased
with the decision.

18
00:03:11,941 --> 00:03:13,943
There's a big crowd.
Do you fear for your life?

19
00:03:14,110 --> 00:03:15,820
No, of course not.

20
00:03:18,489 --> 00:03:19,490
Mr. Estabrook.

21
00:03:19,657 --> 00:03:22,535
As the prosecutor,
how do you feel about the court's decision?

22
00:03:22,702 --> 00:03:24,954
It's happened before,
it'll probably happen again.

23
00:03:25,121 --> 00:03:26,331
I have no more comments.

24
00:03:30,126 --> 00:03:32,170
I'm sorry, no comments. No comments!

25
00:03:32,337 --> 00:03:33,671
I have no comments.

26
00:03:48,811 --> 00:03:51,314
You know what I think?
I'll tell you what I think!

27
00:03:51,481 --> 00:03:53,316
Fuck the courts, that's what I think!

28
00:03:53,483 --> 00:03:57,320
They've already wasted too much time
worrying about the rights of killers!

29
00:03:57,487 --> 00:03:59,489
Ricca, you're a killer!

30
00:04:10,375 --> 00:04:11,751
Get in the car! Go on!

31
00:04:27,141 --> 00:04:30,353
Will you please back off?
We've made all of our comments.

32
00:04:31,980 --> 00:04:34,190
There is nothing that I can add.

33
00:04:38,444 --> 00:04:39,612
Murderer!

34
00:04:59,882 --> 00:05:02,051
Today the noted labor leader
Carmine Ricca...

35
00:05:02,218 --> 00:05:05,680
...was acquitted on a technicality:
the lack of admissible evidence.

36
00:05:06,472 --> 00:05:08,558
Ricca had been charged with complicity...

37
00:05:08,725 --> 00:05:12,562
...in the murders of labor reformer
Anthony Scarza and his family.

38
00:05:12,729 --> 00:05:16,274
When he appeared outside
the courthouse this afternoon, a free man...

39
00:05:16,441 --> 00:05:19,444
...it touched off a wild,
mob-like demonstration.

40
00:05:19,610 --> 00:05:22,488
But the police were finally able
to bring it under control...

41
00:05:22,655 --> 00:05:25,074
...and there have been
no reports of injuries.

42
00:05:25,241 --> 00:05:29,078
But one can expect an uproar
from an angry and alarmed crowd...

43
00:05:29,245 --> 00:05:32,081
...which fully expected Ricca
to be convicted.

44
00:05:32,248 --> 00:05:36,252
And I'm sure we haven't heard
the last of the Ricca case.

45
00:05:36,419 --> 00:05:38,629
Art Brown reporting from city hall.

46
00:06:43,653 --> 00:06:45,071
Cop.

47
00:06:46,447 --> 00:06:47,824
Gino, for chrissake.

48
00:06:47,990 --> 00:06:51,869
Come on, Carmine.
I'm driving this thing like a baby carriage.

49
00:07:46,048 --> 00:07:48,217
Could I see your driver's license, please?

50
00:07:48,384 --> 00:07:50,136
Do you know who that is
sitting back there?

51
00:07:50,303 --> 00:07:53,222
I'll still have to see
your driver's license, please.

52
00:07:53,681 --> 00:07:55,391
I'll have to find it.

53
00:07:55,558 --> 00:07:57,560
Do you know why you're being stopped?

54
00:07:58,895 --> 00:08:02,482
Yes, we know, officer,
and you're making a big mistake.

55
00:08:02,648 --> 00:08:05,526
- You crossed a double line back there.
- A double line?

56
00:08:05,693 --> 00:08:07,236
Take it easy.

57
00:08:07,528 --> 00:08:09,614
Whatever you say, officer.

58
00:08:12,158 --> 00:08:14,202
I just happened to find it, sir.

59
00:08:22,251 --> 00:08:23,920
That's right, Simple Simon.

60
00:08:24,587 --> 00:08:27,590
Check, see if it's stolen.

61
00:08:27,757 --> 00:08:30,092
I want this bastard busted out of his job.

62
00:08:30,259 --> 00:08:34,597
We'll take care of this guy.
You fellas, just take it easy.

63
00:08:46,609 --> 00:08:50,154
- This car registered to you?
- To him.

64
00:08:50,321 --> 00:08:55,159
- I'll have to see the registration.
- Come on, give me that license.

65
00:09:36,492 --> 00:09:39,078
Hi, Harry. Is this your case?

66
00:09:58,514 --> 00:10:00,433
Walter?

67
00:10:02,351 --> 00:10:05,187
Hello, Harry. What are you doing here?

68
00:10:05,354 --> 00:10:07,648
This couldn't have happened
to a nicer bunch.

69
00:10:07,815 --> 00:10:11,777
Ricca, Weinstein, his attorney.
James Cantina, the driver.

70
00:10:11,944 --> 00:10:13,362
What about the bodyguard?

71
00:10:13,529 --> 00:10:15,865
We're checking that out now, lieutenant.

72
00:10:16,032 --> 00:10:19,869
Looks like somebody saved
the taxpayers a lot of money, doesn't it?

73
00:10:20,036 --> 00:10:24,123
Callahan, what are you doing here?
You're on loan to stakeout.

74
00:10:24,290 --> 00:10:27,209
We had nothing hot on,
besides, we were close.

75
00:10:27,376 --> 00:10:31,714
Callahan, you get your lying ass in gear
and get back to that stakeout squad.

76
00:10:31,881 --> 00:10:34,342
Anything else, you call it in.

77
00:10:38,721 --> 00:10:42,558
- Who do you think did this, Briggs?
- You're on loan to stakeout, Callahan.

78
00:10:42,725 --> 00:10:45,269
That's right, lieutenant, you saw to that.

79
00:10:45,436 --> 00:10:48,397
I've got nothing personal
against you, Callahan.

80
00:10:49,065 --> 00:10:51,817
But we can't have the public crying,
"police brutality"...

81
00:10:51,984 --> 00:10:53,611
...every time you're on the street.

82
00:10:53,778 --> 00:10:56,405
You just might need me on a job like this.

83
00:10:56,572 --> 00:10:58,699
Whoever did this was very good at it.

84
00:10:58,866 --> 00:11:00,826
You'd sure be the one to know, Harry.

85
00:11:00,993 --> 00:11:04,246
- Well, I just work for this city, Briggs.
- So do I.

86
00:11:04,747 --> 00:11:06,540
Longer than you.

87
00:11:06,707 --> 00:11:11,045
And I never had to take my gun out
of its holster once. I'm proud of that.

88
00:11:12,421 --> 00:11:14,632
Well, you're a good man, lieutenant.

89
00:11:14,799 --> 00:11:17,426
A good man always knows his limitations.

90
00:11:18,969 --> 00:11:20,596
Lt. Briggs?

91
00:11:22,682 --> 00:11:24,141
Yeah.

92
00:11:25,059 --> 00:11:26,102
What did you get?

93
00:11:26,268 --> 00:11:28,771
Well, it looks like
they were killed with a Magnum.

94
00:11:28,938 --> 00:11:32,775
The boys now are checking
the blood types and for fingerprints.

95
00:11:35,736 --> 00:11:37,113
What do you have?

96
00:11:37,279 --> 00:11:42,243
Driver's license. Doesn't look at all
like the usual gangster crap, does it?

97
00:11:42,410 --> 00:11:45,287
Briggs has his nose up his ass today.

98
00:11:46,122 --> 00:11:49,291
I guess he thinks
that's where his promotion is.

99
00:11:49,458 --> 00:11:51,293
See you later, Harry.

100
00:11:52,795 --> 00:11:54,797
What's with you and Briggs anyway?

101
00:11:54,964 --> 00:11:56,590
Jealousy.

102
00:11:56,757 --> 00:12:00,886
He knows this is the kind of case
I should be on. It's just a matter of time.

103
00:12:01,470 --> 00:12:03,806
Hey, Early, wanna get in on this?

104
00:12:05,474 --> 00:12:06,976
What the hell is that about?

105
00:12:07,143 --> 00:12:10,479
They're giving odds on how long
you'll stay alive being my partner.

106
00:12:10,646 --> 00:12:13,107
- Are you kidding?
- Nope.

107
00:12:13,274 --> 00:12:14,942
How long did your last partner go?

108
00:12:15,109 --> 00:12:16,193
A couple of weeks.

109
00:12:16,360 --> 00:12:19,530
Don't worry, he's still alive,
teaching college.

110
00:12:20,656 --> 00:12:22,199
You have another trade, Smith?

111
00:12:22,366 --> 00:12:25,703
- No, no. Do you?
- No, but Bill Mackenzie does.

112
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:27,955
Who in the hell is Bill Mackenzie?

113
00:12:28,122 --> 00:12:31,041
He's an ex-Homicide man,
has a snack shop out at the airport.

114
00:12:31,208 --> 00:12:33,502
Greatest burgers in town. Hungry?

115
00:12:33,961 --> 00:12:37,423
- How can you be hungry after seeing that?
- Seeing what?

116
00:12:54,440 --> 00:12:58,444
So Ricca finally bought it.
There must be hope for the world yet.

117
00:12:58,611 --> 00:13:00,529
How about you? Do you want something?

118
00:13:00,696 --> 00:13:04,658
- We got chili and garlic bread today.
- No, thank you. I don't feel very hungry.

119
00:13:04,825 --> 00:13:08,245
In broad daylight at close range?
Must've looked like ripe melons.

120
00:13:10,539 --> 00:13:13,542
Operations Supervisor, Mr. Phoenix,
use white courtesy telephone.

121
00:13:13,709 --> 00:13:15,211
Now all keep calm.

122
00:13:18,380 --> 00:13:20,466
I'll never forget the Floyd case.

123
00:13:20,633 --> 00:13:22,760
Got it with an axe during the rush hour.

124
00:13:23,385 --> 00:13:24,887
How about some cream pie?

125
00:13:25,054 --> 00:13:27,681
- Operations Supervisor, Mr. Phoenix...
- I don't think so.

126
00:13:27,848 --> 00:13:30,184
- ... use white courtesy telephone.
- Must be trouble.

127
00:13:30,351 --> 00:13:32,812
That's the airport code-name for trouble.

128
00:13:32,978 --> 00:13:38,901
American Airlines flight 577,
flagship, nonstop for Washington...

129
00:13:39,068 --> 00:13:41,779
...may now be boarded at Gate 5.

130
00:13:41,946 --> 00:13:46,242
American Airlines, final call, flight 577...

131
00:13:46,408 --> 00:13:49,203
...flagship for Washington...

132
00:13:49,370 --> 00:13:53,123
...boarding at Gate 5.
All aboard, please.

133
00:14:17,606 --> 00:14:20,442
We've got 90 people being terrorized
by those maniacs...

134
00:14:20,609 --> 00:14:22,278
...in boarding area B right now.

135
00:14:22,444 --> 00:14:25,406
What's taking so long?
They said they'd be there in 15 minutes.

136
00:14:25,573 --> 00:14:26,949
Where's that overseas pilot?

137
00:14:27,116 --> 00:14:29,785
I don't understand.
How did they get through security?

138
00:14:29,952 --> 00:14:31,829
- I don't know.
- Any problem here?

139
00:14:31,996 --> 00:14:33,455
What are you doing here?

140
00:14:33,622 --> 00:14:36,333
- I'm sorry, you'll have to leave.
- I'm a police officer.

141
00:14:36,625 --> 00:14:40,212
We've got two frantic hijackers
on our New York flight.

142
00:14:40,796 --> 00:14:43,799
- Have you called the FBI?
- They're on their way here right now.

143
00:14:43,966 --> 00:14:46,802
But the hijackers want an overseas pilot
before they take off.

144
00:14:50,472 --> 00:14:52,975
May I make a suggestion?

145
00:15:25,841 --> 00:15:27,176
Good afternoon.

146
00:15:27,343 --> 00:15:30,429
You took your goddamn time about it.
Now, close that door!

147
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:32,389
All right, what's in there?

148
00:15:33,515 --> 00:15:35,684
Overseas charts and flight plans.

149
00:15:35,851 --> 00:15:37,603
Set it down!

150
00:15:38,854 --> 00:15:40,522
All right, turn around.

151
00:15:46,362 --> 00:15:48,030
Stay there.

152
00:15:57,331 --> 00:15:59,166
All right, turn around here.

153
00:15:59,875 --> 00:16:02,044
Here! Now get in there.

154
00:16:04,421 --> 00:16:08,676
- It's all yours now.
- All right, get this thing up!

155
00:16:11,512 --> 00:16:13,389
Where to?

156
00:16:13,555 --> 00:16:17,101
You get us up,
I'll tell you where to when we're up.

157
00:16:21,730 --> 00:16:24,191
You wanna put us in take-off position?

158
00:16:29,071 --> 00:16:30,406
Starting three.

159
00:17:25,627 --> 00:17:26,795
Move it!

160
00:17:28,797 --> 00:17:30,299
All right, I'll take it.

161
00:18:01,038 --> 00:18:04,333
That's right, lieutenant. We were lucky
to have one of your men here.

162
00:18:04,500 --> 00:18:06,877
He's onboard now, an Inspector Callahan.

163
00:18:07,336 --> 00:18:08,504
Callahan!

164
00:18:25,521 --> 00:18:29,191
Excuse me, captain.
I know this may sound silly...

165
00:18:29,358 --> 00:18:30,818
...but can you fly?

166
00:18:31,527 --> 00:18:35,114
No. Never had a lesson.

167
00:19:02,891 --> 00:19:03,892
Sit down!

168
00:19:48,103 --> 00:19:51,064
What are you doing here, lieutenant?

169
00:20:16,381 --> 00:20:18,091
Hi, Harry.

170
00:20:24,139 --> 00:20:27,976
Harry. You crazy son of a bitch.
I could've killed you.

171
00:20:28,143 --> 00:20:30,979
Yeah, I noticed that, Charlie.
What the hell you doing?

172
00:20:31,146 --> 00:20:33,065
I haven't seen you in a coon's age.

173
00:20:33,232 --> 00:20:37,027
I been meaning to drop by,
but we've been kind of busy.

174
00:20:37,194 --> 00:20:40,948
Yeah, well,
I ain't living with Carol anymore.

175
00:20:41,490 --> 00:20:42,658
Sorry to hear that.

176
00:20:42,824 --> 00:20:47,829
Yeah. It's my third time at bat.

177
00:20:48,497 --> 00:20:49,831
Where's the time go?

178
00:20:51,166 --> 00:20:53,001
I'm afraid of time.

179
00:20:53,168 --> 00:20:57,756
I know you 10 years already, ever since
I first came out here, you realize that?

180
00:20:57,923 --> 00:21:01,843
You don't look older to me.
Do I look older to you?

181
00:21:04,346 --> 00:21:06,807
Why don't you put in
for some desk work, Charlie?

182
00:21:06,974 --> 00:21:08,725
You don't need the streets anymore.

183
00:21:08,892 --> 00:21:11,061
We should've put our 20 in the Marines.

184
00:21:11,353 --> 00:21:15,315
These days,
a cop kills a hoodlum on the street...

185
00:21:15,482 --> 00:21:17,859
...he might as well just dump
the body someplace.

186
00:21:18,026 --> 00:21:20,362
Because those snot-nosed
young bastards...

187
00:21:20,529 --> 00:21:24,032
...down at the DA's office will crucify them
one way or another.

188
00:21:24,199 --> 00:21:27,077
A hood can kill a cop,
but let a cop kill a hood...

189
00:21:27,661 --> 00:21:29,413
Am I right?

190
00:21:30,872 --> 00:21:35,210
You put in plenty of time,
why don't you go for retirement?

191
00:21:35,377 --> 00:21:37,462
What the hell, you don't need this.

192
00:21:37,629 --> 00:21:41,508
I know you 10 years.
I'll tell you something, I'll never retire.

193
00:21:41,675 --> 00:21:43,802
Never.

194
00:21:44,553 --> 00:21:46,722
I'm going out fighting.

195
00:21:47,264 --> 00:21:50,350
That's the only way to go. Am I right?

196
00:22:43,528 --> 00:22:44,696
You boys rookies?

197
00:22:44,863 --> 00:22:46,782
Yes, sir. Traffic.

198
00:22:46,948 --> 00:22:49,951
I'm John Davis. This is Phil Sweet.

199
00:22:50,118 --> 00:22:53,288
That's Red Astrachan, Mike Grimes.

200
00:22:53,455 --> 00:22:56,124
- You're Inspector Harry Callahan, no?
- That's right.

201
00:22:56,291 --> 00:22:59,211
What are you doing here?
Don't you have regular times for this?

202
00:22:59,378 --> 00:23:02,130
You shouldn't be on the streets
if you can't shoot well.

203
00:23:02,297 --> 00:23:05,759
- Killers don't make allowances.
- You're in big trouble.

204
00:23:05,926 --> 00:23:07,135
Can't fault you there.

205
00:23:07,302 --> 00:23:09,805
Are you shooting
in the combat championship next week?

206
00:23:09,971 --> 00:23:11,014
I always do.

207
00:23:11,181 --> 00:23:14,643
- You win every year, don't you?
- Became sort of an institution around here.

208
00:23:14,810 --> 00:23:17,479
Yes, sir, we've heard all about you.

209
00:23:18,772 --> 00:23:22,442
This is about the only time
I get this place alone.

210
00:23:22,609 --> 00:23:25,320
We'll leave if you'd like
the range to yourself.

211
00:23:28,990 --> 00:23:30,492
No, that's all right.

212
00:23:32,619 --> 00:23:35,163
What kind of a load
do you use in that. 44?

213
00:23:35,330 --> 00:23:36,665
A light special.

214
00:23:36,832 --> 00:23:39,543
This size gun gives me better control
and less recoil...

215
00:23:39,709 --> 00:23:42,337
...than a. 357 Magnum with wadcutters.

216
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:13,702
That's not bad.

217
00:24:15,537 --> 00:24:16,580
Care to try?

218
00:24:16,746 --> 00:24:18,373
No, sir. No, I don't think so.

219
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:21,209
- Come on, give it a try.
- Go on, Sweet.

220
00:24:24,880 --> 00:24:26,173
I'm farsighted.

221
00:24:31,386 --> 00:24:33,388
Don't drop it.

222
00:24:52,282 --> 00:24:53,658
Hey, that's not bad.

223
00:24:53,909 --> 00:24:57,245
Well, I think it's just a little
heavy for me. I missed one.

224
00:24:57,412 --> 00:24:58,955
You'll get used to it.

225
00:24:59,122 --> 00:25:01,333
Where did you learn to shoot?
Not around here.

226
00:25:01,500 --> 00:25:04,878
No, sir, no.
Airborne Rangers, Special Forces.

227
00:25:06,254 --> 00:25:08,256
And the rest of these guys, even close?

228
00:25:08,423 --> 00:25:11,259
Well, Grimes here, he's...

229
00:25:11,426 --> 00:25:13,428
I guess he's about even with me.

230
00:25:13,595 --> 00:25:16,723
- Astrachan's a little better on a good day.
- A little bit.

231
00:25:16,890 --> 00:25:20,101
And Davis is just dog nuts.
He's a lot better.

232
00:25:20,894 --> 00:25:25,857
A lot better? Sure show a sense of style.
Sweet, is it?

233
00:25:26,024 --> 00:25:27,275
Yes, sir.

234
00:25:27,442 --> 00:25:30,403
When I get back on Homicide,
I hope you boys will come see me.

235
00:25:30,570 --> 00:25:32,572
- Good.
- Thank you very much, we'd like that.

236
00:25:32,739 --> 00:25:34,157
Let's go!

237
00:25:34,324 --> 00:25:36,243
- Good night, sir.
- Good night.

238
00:25:37,994 --> 00:25:39,788
Who buys? The sun was in my eyes.

239
00:25:39,955 --> 00:25:43,291
- You got to be on, Grimes.
- The sun is always in your eyes.

240
00:25:43,458 --> 00:25:46,962
How come I always have to buy
the beer for you turkeys?

241
00:25:48,338 --> 00:25:50,715
Where do you want to go?

242
